<bioghist encodinganalog="545$a">
<head>Biographical Information
</head>
<p>Chris Burnside is a choreographer, performer, and a former dance professor at Virginia Commonwealth University. He has a BFA in Communication Arts and Design from VCU and an MM in Dance from Florida State University. His dance and performance work ranges from complete choreography to movement monologues. He has performed in New York City, Los Angeles, Washington, D.C., and several other locations along the East Coast.  For a more detailed look at his decision to move from New York City to Richmond to teach at VCU and his successful and varied career as an openly gay performer and professor, see â€œA Brief Narrativeâ€ by Chris Burnside in this collection.
</p>
</bioghist>

<scopecontent encodinganalog="520$a">
<head>Scope and Content
</head>
<p>These papers document Chris Burnsideâ€™s performances, which span from 1981 to 2009.  It primarily includes reproductions of the articles and the digitized performances, which were digitized from various media storage formats by VCU Libraries.  The material was placed on loan by Chris Burnside. The original media formats were returned to him after digitization by VCU Libraries.  Other materials include flyers, posters, promotional pamphlets, exhibition books, and correspondence.  Of particular note are the items that relate to the Grace Street Theaterâ€™s restoration from the Lee Art Theater and the event that coincided with its reopening, for which Burnside composed a benediction.
</p>
<p>Burnside studied dance under Richard Carlyon and performed in his honor at VCU event. His papers include an invitational pamphlet and articles about the event. Outside of the Chris Burnside Papers, Special Collections and Archives houses the exhibition catalog for <title render="italic">Richard Carlyon: A Retrospective</title> in book collection stacks under the call number N 6512 .C37 A4 2009. </p>
</scopecontent>

<arrangement encodinganalog="351">
<head>Arrangement
</head>
<p>The Chris Burnside Papers are arranged in four series.  The series arrangement is as follows:
</p>
<p>Series 1: Performances, 1984-2009</p>
<p>
This series includes specific performances in which Burnside participated and choreographed.  The arrangement of this series reflects the lenderâ€™s original order. The folders are primarily in alphabetical order by performance/event name and then in chronological order if the event shares its name. Some of the dances were performed or were written about in the press over multiple years, but all materials related to a specific dance are placed together.  Items in this series include flyers, publications, announcements, reviews, and other materials associated with each performance.  
</p>
<p>Series 2: Other materials, 1981-2009</p>
<p>This series consists of materials that fit into the wider scope of his career and life as they relate to dance, performance, and other activities.  The folders are in alphabetical order and include a reflective biographical essay, a paper about the future of dance, and other articles and reviews. 
</p>
<p>
Series 3: Digitized performances, undated</p>
<p>This series consists of digitally captured performances spanning the years of the collection.  Each file is named for the title of the performance in alphabetical order followed by a number denoting different versions of the same performance. The digital content is stored on a Lacie Grand external hard drive.
</p>
<p>
Series 4: Oversized Posters, 1988-2007</p>
<p>This series includes the oversized posters stored in the flat files.  They are arranged in alphabetical order.</p>
</arrangement>







